{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "System Identification and Conductor Role",
    "objective": "Identify a TN-C-S system and differentiate the functional role of bonding versus circuit protection within that specific arrangement.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In a TN-C-S system, the supplier provides a combined Neutral and Earth (PEN) conductor which is split at the intake. This is often referred to as PME (Protective Multiple Earthing).",
      "Once inside the installation, we must distinguish between conductors based on their function. A Circuit Protective Conductor (CPC) is part of a specific circuit, while Main Protective Bonding connects the Main Earthing Terminal (MET) to incoming metallic services like water or gas pipes to ensure an equipotential zone."
    ],
    "questionText": "A housing development uses a supply where the Neutral and Earth are combined in the street cable but split into separate terminals at the property's cutout. You observe a thick green/yellow conductor connecting the Main Earthing Terminal (MET) to the incoming copper water main. Identify this earthing system type and explain why that specific conductor is defined as Main Protective Bonding rather than a Circuit Protective Conductor (CPC).",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The earthing system is TN-C-S (or PME).",
      "The conductor is Main Protective Bonding because its function is to equalize the electrical potential (voltage) of the incoming metal water service to the MET.",
      "It is not a CPC because a CPC is dedicated to connecting the metal parts of an individual electrical circuit back to the MET to provide a fault path."
    ],
    "hint": "Focus on the 'Combined' nature of the supply for the system name, and think about whether the water pipe is an electrical circuit or an incoming service."
  }
}

